<li id="cite_note-ohehir2013-3"><span class="mw-cite-backlink">^ <a href="#cite_ref-ohehir2013_3-0"><sup><i><b>a</b></i></sup></a> <a href="#cite_ref-ohehir2013_3-1"><sup><i><b>b</b></i></sup></a></span> <span class="reference-text"><cite id="CITEREFO&#39;Hehir2013" class="citation web cs1">O'Hehir, Andrew (November 13, 2013). <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="http://www.salon.com/2013/11/13/dear_mr_watterson_remembering_the_last_great_newspaper_comic/">"<span class="cs1-kern-left">'</span>Dear Mr. Watterson': Remembering the last great newspaper comic"</a>. <i><a href="/wiki/Salon_(website)" title="Salon (website)">Salon</a></i>. San Francisco, California: Salon Media Group. <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://web.archive.org/web/20150924100511/http://www.salon.com/2013/11/13/dear_mr_watterson_remembering_the_last_great_newspaper_comic/">Archived</a> from the original on September 24, 2015<span class="reference-accessdate">. Retrieved <span class="nowrap">November 21,</span> 2015</span>. <q>'Calvin and Hobbes' has been immensely influential – but mostly in TV animation, in stand-up and sketch comedy, and in graphic novels and in Internet culture. The newspaper comic, like the newspaper itself, has lost its social meaning.</q></cite><span title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Ajournal&amp;rft.genre=unknown&amp;rft.jtitle=Salon&amp;rft.atitle=%27Dear+Mr.+Watterson%27%3A+Remembering+the+last+great+newspaper+comic&amp;rft.date=2013-11-13&amp;rft.aulast=O%27Hehir&amp;rft.aufirst=Andrew&amp;rft_id=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.salon.com%2F2013%2F11%2F13%2Fdear_mr_watterson_remembering_the_last_great_newspaper_comic%2F&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3ACalvin+and+Hobbes" class="Z3988"></span><link rel="mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href="mw-data:TemplateStyles:r951705291"/></span>
</li>
